    "summary": "Deir el-Medina was a settlement on the west bank of the Nile near ancient Thebes, occupied approximately 1500–1077 BC, that housed the skilled craftsmen and their families responsible for constructing and decorating the royal tombs in the [[event:1811|Valley of the Kings]] and the Valley of the Queens during the [[event:60|New Kingdom Egypt]]. The village is unique in the archaeological record because the exceptional literacy of its inhabitants — who needed to read and write for their professional work — combined with the dry desert conditions that preserved organic materials, has produced an unparalleled archive of ancient everyday life.\n\nThousands of ostraca (inscribed pottery fragments and stone flakes) found at the site record work rosters, absence excuses, legal disputes, love poetry, dream interpretations, hymns, and literary compositions. Among the most historically significant texts are records of the first known labor strikes in history: workers at Deir el-Medina during the reign of Ramesses III walked off the job to protest non-payment of their grain rations, a crisis documented in detail on surviving administrative papyri. The texts also preserve personal correspondence, wills, and records of petty crimes, giving historians direct access to the concerns and voices of non-elite ancient Egyptians.\n\nThe village's architecture is well preserved, with rows of narrow attached houses lining a central street, giving a clear picture of working-class New Kingdom domestic space. The tombs that the villagers built for themselves, though small by royal standards, are richly decorated with scenes revealing popular religious beliefs about the afterlife that differ in interesting ways from official royal funerary tradition.",
